# Next.js Frontend Conventions

## Server vs Client Components
- Default to Server Components. Add `"use client"` only when the file needs state, effects, refs, or browser APIs.
- Keep client components small and leaf-like. Fetch on the server; pass data down as props.

## Data Fetching
- The frontend talks to `apps/api` via the typed client at `apps/web/src/lib/api.ts`. No direct Prisma, no direct DB.
- Read the API base URL from env (`API_URL` on server, `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL` on client). Never hardcode URLs.
- Server Components `await` the API client directly. Client Components use React Query (or SWR) — pick one and stick to it.

## Component Rules
- Components render. They do not own business rules (position sizing, P&L math, order validation). Those live in the backend.
- Formatting (currency, dates, percentages) lives in `apps/web/src/lib/format.ts` — one source of truth.
- No deep-tree `fetch` calls. Colocate data loading near the route segment (`page.tsx` / `layout.tsx`).

## State
- URL state (filters, selected tab, symbol) goes in search params.
- Server state: React Query / SWR. No duplicating it into a global store.
- Local UI state: `useState`. No Redux / Zustand until a concrete need appears.

## Example

```tsx
// ✅ Server Component fetches once; client chart stays lean
// app/(dashboard)/portfolio/page.tsx
export default async function PortfolioPage() {
  const positions = await api.portfolio.list();
  return <PositionsTable positions={positions} />;
}
```

## Don't
- No `any` on API responses. Import the shared types or generated client.
- No business logic "ported" from the backend for speed. Ask the API.
- No `process.env.X` sprinkled through components. Centralize in `apps/web/src/lib/env.ts`.
